com.yahoo.bullet.typesystem

Class TypedObject

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.yahoo.bullet.typesystem.TypedObject
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable

    public class TypedObject
extends Object
implements Serializable
    Represents an object with its Type. Note that these objects must be Serializable.

      • TypedObject

        public TypedObject(Serializable value)

        Parameters:

      • TypedObject

        public TypedObject(Type type,
                   Serializable value)
        Create a TypedObject with the given non-null type. Note that the value is not validated to be of that type. If it is not, all operation results are undefined. You should use Type.cast(Serializable) or Type.forceCast(Type, Serializable) to force the value to the desired type if it is not.
        Parameters:
        type - The type of the value.
        value - The value being wrapped.

      • containsKey

        public Boolean containsKey(String key)
        Returns true if the value (or its underlying values) contains a mapping for the specified non-null key. Returns null if there exists no mapping for the specified non-null key but the value (or its underlying values) contains a null key or the value contains a null underlying value. Always returns null if the value or specified key is null. Returns false otherwise. Only Type.COMPLEX_LISTS and Type.MAPS support getting a mapping.
        Parameters:
        key - The key to be tested.
        Returns:
        A Boolean to indicate if the value or its underlying values contain a mapping for the specified key.
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if not supported.

      • containsValue

        public Boolean containsValue(TypedObject target)
        Returns true if the value or its underlying values contain the specified value. Returns null if the value or its underlying values does not contain the specified value but contains a null value(s). Returns false otherwise. Only LIST and MAP are supported.
        Parameters:
        target - The target TypedObject to be tested.
        Returns:
        A Boolean to indicate if the value or its underlying values contain the specified value.
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if not supported.

      • equalTo

        public Boolean equalTo(TypedObject target)
        Returns true if this equals the specified object. The object can be a TypedObject or be constructed as a TypedObject. Note that this is not the same as equals(Object). This will do a safe cast to unify Type.NUMERICS and compare. This will basically use compareTo(TypedObject) and check if the result is 0.
        Parameters:
        target - The object to compare to.
        Returns:
        A Boolean to indicate if this equals the specified object.

      • compareTo

        public Integer compareTo(TypedObject other)
        Compares this TypedObject to another. Only works on objects that have a type in Type.PRIMITIVES. If either object is of Type.NULL, then null is returned. Otherwise, an exception will be thrown when comparing objects whose types are not in Type.PRIMITIVES. This will force Type.NUMERICS that are not of the same Type to Double instances to compare them. Otherwise, works like Comparable.compareTo(Object).
        Parameters:
        other - The other non-null TypedObject.
        Returns:
        An Integer that works like Comparable.compareTo(Object) or null if either objects were null.
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the other object could not compared to this.

      • nullsFirst

        public static Comparator<TypedObject> nullsFirst()
        Returns a Comparator for TypedObject that, unlike compareTo(TypedObject), will work on any one TypedObject being NULL. In particular, this comparator will place nulls first when sorting by it. If the first object is NULL, the comparator will return Integer.MIN_VALUE. If the second object is NULL, the comparator will return Integer.MIN_VALUE. Otherwise, the standard compareTo(TypedObject) will be invoked. Note this comparator only works on non-null objects, i.e. the TypedObject arguments must not be null.
        Returns:
        A Comparator that can places NULL objects first.

      • nullsLast

        public static Comparator<TypedObject> nullsLast()
        This is simply the Comparator.reversed() on the nullsFirst() Comparator. See docs for that method. This method places NULL objects last.
        Returns:
        A Comparator that can places NULL objects last.

      • safeCastFromObject

        public static TypedObject safeCastFromObject(Type type,
                                             Serializable object)
        Takes an object and returns a casted TypedObject according to the given type. Note that this only casts safely. It can widen numeric types if loss of precision does not occur. See Type.cast(Serializable).
        Parameters:
        type - The Type to cast the values to.
        object - The Object that is being cast.
        Returns:
        The casted TypedObject with the Type or UNKNOWN if the cast failed.

      • forceCastStringToNumber

        public static TypedObject forceCastStringToNumber(Serializable value)
        Takes a non-null value and returns a numeric TypedObject - it has a type in Type.NUMERICS. The value is then a Number. It uses the String representation of the object to cast it.
        Parameters:
        value - The Object value that is being cast to a numeric.
        Returns:
        The casted TypedObject with the type set to numeric or UNKNOWN if not.
